        =\n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n}}\n'''Tajarhi''', '''Tegerhi''' or  '''Tajirhi''' ({{lang-ar|\u062a\u062c\u0631\u0647\u064a}}) is an oasis and crossroads village in the [[Murzuq District]] of [[Libya]]. It lies in the [[Sahara Desert]] and is the last refueling point in Libya before reaching [[Madama]], the first station in Niger (after the unpopulated frontier station at [[Tummo]]), some 282 kilometers to the south,<ref name=\"Tajarhi- FR\">[http://www.fallingrain.com/world/LY/30/Tajarhi.html \"Tajarhi, Libya\"] Falling Rain Genomics, Inc.</ref> or 361&nbsp;km by track.<ref>[http://www.wikiloc.com/wikiloc/view.do?id=424300 \"TAD 05 Tajarhi Madama\"] Wikiloc, with map</ref> Tajarhi has an airstrip (HL-57) south of town.<ref name=\"Tajarhi- FR\"/>\n\n==History==\nTajarhi was and still is the southernmost village in [[Fezzan]], located at the desert trade routes to the [[Niger River]], [[Lake Chad]] and the [[Sudan (region)|Sudan]].<ref name=\"Bruce\">Bruce-Lockhart, Jamie (2008) ''A sailor in the Sahara: the life and travels in Africa of Hugh Clapperton, Commander RN'' I. B. Tauris, London, [https://books.google.com/books?id=ROM0qi5UjU8C&pg=PA102 pages 102-103], {{ISBN|978-1-84511-479-4}}</ref> Among the goods traded north were slaves,<ref name=\"Lovejoy\">Lovejoy, Paul E. (2004) ''Slavery on the frontiers of Islam'' Markus Wiener Publishers, Princeton, New Jersey, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=T4w3xWn1yGAC&pg=PA41 page 41], {{ISBN|1-55876-328-7}}</ref> and the trade in slaves through Tajarhi increased after Tunisia and Algeria abolished the trade in 1846 and 1848, respectively.<ref>Abun-Nasr, Jamil M. (1987) ''A History of the Maghrib in the Islamic Period'' Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, UK, page 316, {{ISBN|0-521-33767-4}}</ref> Tajarhi was described by British naval officer [[George Francis Lyon]] in 1819 as a lush oasis with groves of date palms and wild ducks on the brackish lakes.<ref name=\"Bruce\"/>\n\nBeginning in 2004, a paved road has been built from [[Al Qatrun]] via Tajahi up until the Libyan border with Niger at [[Tumo (Sahara)|Tumo]]. In this section, the long-distance road directly follows the very old caravan route from [[Tripoli]]/[[Sirte]] in the North to Lake Chad in the South, also known as [[Trans-Saharan trade|Bilma Trail]] or [[Garamantes|Garamantean]] Road.\n\n==Notes==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.maplandia.com/libya/murzuq/tajarhi/ \"Tajarhi Map \u2014 Satellite Images of Tajarhi\"] Maplandia\n* [http://www.dimensioneavventura.org/image3/libia_rollers/libia_rollers.htm \"Libia - Wan Am Hamus\"], in Italian\n{{-}}\n{{Murzuq}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Murzuq District]]\n[[Category:Sahara]]\n", "name_user": "Sinaloa", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tajarhi"}
{"title_page": "L\u00e9on Com\u00e8s", "text_new": "{{short description|French cyclist}}\n[[File:L\u00e9on Com\u00e8s.jpg|thumb|1909]]\n[[File:Hourlier-Com\u00e9s Vel d'hiv 18.1.1914 Six jours.jpg|thumb|left|250px|L\u00e9on Hourlier and L\u00e9on Com\u00e8s, Paris Six Days, 1914]]\n'''L\u00e9on Com\u00e8s''' (11 February 1889 - 17 October 1915) was a [[French people|French]] [[cycling|cyclist]]. He was born in [[Perpignan]], [[France]]. Com\u00e8s won the French national cycling championships in 1909, 1911 and 1914. He also won the [[French Grand Prix]] in 1914. Both Com\u00e8s and his brother-in-law and fellow cyclist [[L\u00e9on Hourlier]] enlisted in the French military during [[World War I]]. They died together in a military air accident at [[Saint-Etienne-au-Temple]] in the Champagne district in France.<ref name=cycarch>{{cycling archives|23285}}</ref><ref name=ts>[[Thames Star]], [http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=THS19160103.2.7.2&e=-------50--101----0Circassia-- Issue 14984, 3 January 1916, Page 2]</ref><ref name=pitt>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yxsbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OUkEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5163,2804111&dq=rugby+killed&hl=en Athletes Killed in European War.] [[The Pittsburgh Press]] - Nov 10, 1915.</ref>\n\nIn 1908 he placed 3rd in the French National Championship sprint and the following year took 1st in the GP Angers spring.  In 1914 he placed 1st, along with his brother-in-law L\u00e9on Hourlier, in the Paris Six Days.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Comes, Leon}}\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:1915 deaths]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:French military personnel killed in World War I]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Perpignan]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:L\u00e9on Com\u00e8s.jpg|thumb|1909]]\n[[File:Hourlier-Com\u00e9s Vel d'hiv 18.1.1914 Six jours.jpg|thumb|left|250px|L\u00e9on Hourlier and L\u00e9on Com\u00e8s, Paris Six Days, 1914]]\n'''L\u00e9on Com\u00e8s''' (11 February 1889 - 17 October 1915) was a [[French people|French]] [[cycling|cyclist]]. He was born in [[Perpignan]], [[France]]. Com\u00e8s won the French national cycling championships in 1909, 1911 and 1914. He also won the [[French Grand Prix]] in 1914. Both Com\u00e8s and his brother-in-law and fellow cyclist [[L\u00e9on Hourlier]] enlisted in the French military during [[World War I]]. They died together in a military air accident at [[Saint-Etienne-au-Temple]] in the Champagne district in France.<ref name=cycarch>{{cycling archives|23285}}</ref><ref name=ts>[[Thames Star]], [http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=THS19160103.2.7.2&e=-------50--101----0Circassia-- Issue 14984, 3 January 1916, Page 2]</ref><ref name=pitt>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yxsbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OUkEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5163,2804111&dq=rugby+killed&hl=en Athletes Killed in European War.] [[The Pittsburgh Press]] - Nov 10, 1915.</ref>\n\nIn 1908 he placed 3rd in the French National Championship sprint and the following year took 1st in the GP Angers spring.  In 1914 he placed 1st, along with his brother-in-law L\u00e9on Hourlier, in the Paris Six Days.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Comes, Leon}}\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:1915 deaths]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:French military personnel killed in World War I]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Perpignan]]\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L%C3%A9on_Com%C3%A8s"}
{"title_page": "Please Yourself", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Refimprove|date=June 2011}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Please Yourself\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Bananarama]]\n| cover      = Banana_py.JPG\n| alt        =\n| released   = 29 March 1993\n| recorded   = July 1991 \u2013 May 1992\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]], [[dance-pop]], [[disco]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[London Records|London]]\n| producer   = [[Stock Aitken Waterman|Stock & Waterman]]\n| prev_title = [[Pop Life (Bananarama album)|Pop Life]]\n| prev_year  = 1991\n| next_title = [[Bunch of Hits]]\n| next_year  = 1993\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Please Yourself\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Movin' On (Bananarama song)|Movin' On]]\n | single1date = August 1992<ref name=occ>{{cite web|title=Bananarama - Full Official Chart History|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/30294/bananarama/|website=Official Charts Company|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=19 January 2016}}</ref>\n | single2     = [[Last Thing on My Mind (Bananarama song)|Last Thing on My Mind]]\n | single2date = November 1992<ref name=\"occ\"/>\n | single3     = [[More, More, More#Bananarama version|More, More, More]]\n | single3date = March 1993<ref name=\"occ\"/>\n}}\n}}\n'''''Please Yourself''''' is the sixth studio album by British [[girl group]] [[Bananarama]]. It was released in 1993 by [[London Records]], the last release the group had on this label. It is also the first album from Bananarama as a duo \u2013 with original members [[Sara Dallin]] and [[Keren Woodward]] continuing after the departure of [[Jacquie O'Sullivan]] in 1991 and the last to feature both [[Sara Dallin]] and [[Keren Woodward]] to play bass guitar on some tracks on the album until ''[[Viva (Bananarama album)|Viva]]''.  ''Please Yourself'' also reunites Bananarama with two-thirds of the [[Stock Aitken Waterman]] production team (Stock and Waterman). Musician Gary Miller was brought in to do keyboards and guitar and would be Bananarama's next collaborator on their next album ''[[Ultra Violet (Bananarama album)|Ultra Violet]]''. The concept of the album was first suggested by Pete Waterman as 'ABBA-Banana', a record that would feature pop songs in the style of [[ABBA]], but updated for the 1990s{{cn|date=September 2018}}.\n\n''Please Yourself'' features songs in a [[Europop]] style. It is the first Bananarama album not to get a release in the United States, and upon its release in the UK, it was panned by critics and charted at a low number forty-six.<ref name=\"occ\"/> There was a limited double CD edition featuring 12\" remix of former hit singles. Dallin and Woodward have later admitted in interviews that they are not fond of this album{{cn|date=September 2018}}. Two of the songs on the album would later be recycled by Pete Waterman over five years later for use with the band [[Steps (group)|Steps]]- \"[[Last Thing on My Mind (Bananarama song)#Steps version|Last Thing on My Mind]]\" would be their second single and the track \"[[Movin' On (Bananarama song)|Movin' On]]\" would be included on their second album ''[[Steptacular]]''.\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs written by [[Sara Dallin]], [[Keren Woodward]], [[Mike Stock (musician)|Mike Stock]] and [[Pete Waterman]], except where noted.\n\n'''CD and cassette versions'''\n#\"[[Movin' On (Bananarama song)|Movin' On]]\" \u2013 4:38 \n#\"[[Last Thing on My Mind (Bananarama song)|Last Thing on My Mind]]\" \u2013 3:35\n#\"Let Me Love You One More Time\" \u2013 3:39\n#\"[[More, More, More#Bananarama version|More, More, More]]\" \u2013 3:08 <small>(G. Diamond, S. Dallin, K. Woodward, M. Stock, P. Waterman)</small>\n#\"Is She Good to You\" \u2013 3:44 \n#\"Only Time Will Tell\" \u2013 3:35 \n#\"Give It All Up for Love\" \u2013 3:57\n#\"You'll Never Know What It Means\" \u2013 4:36 \n#\"You're Never Satisfied\" \u2013 3: