t member [[Kevin Nealon]] appears during Weekend Update to tell viewers he is not on ''SNL'' anymore and that viewers who do see him are watching reruns from the 1990s that at the time aired on [[Comedy Central]].\n*[[Winona Ryder]] appears during The Weekend Update Cliffhanger.\n*[[Jerry Minor]]'s final episode as a cast member.\n*[[Chris Parnell]]'s final episode as a cast member (until the middle of the [[Saturday Night Live (season 27)|next season]]).\n|LineColor=235454\n}}\n}}</onlyinclude>\n\n==Specials==\n{{#invoke:Episode table|main\n|background=#235454\n|title=\n|airdate=\n|episodes=\n\n{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Saturday Night Live (season 26)\n|LineColor=235454\n|Title=2000 Presidential Bash\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2000|11|3}}\n|ShortSummary=The special included election material from this year and years past. Rachel Dratch, Will Ferrell and Darrell Hammond hosted the special while doing a number of different impressions. This special also featured cameo appearances from George W. Bush, Al Gore, [[Jesse Ventura]], [[George H.W. Bush]], [[Barbara Bush]] and [[Dana Carvey]].\n}}\n\n{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Saturday Night Live (season 26)\n|LineColor=235454\n|Title=Thursday Night Live (1) \n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|2|1}}\n|ShortSummary=\"The Culps' Mandatory Drug Awareness Assembly\" sketch from this episode was included in the prime-time special \"SNL Mother's Day Special 2001\" as well as the clip show \"The Best of Will Ferrell\".\n}}\n\n{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Saturday Night Live (season 26)\n|LineColor=235454\n|Title=Thursday Night Live (2) \n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|2|8}}\n|ShortSummary=\n}}\n\n{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Saturday Night Live (season 26)\n|LineColor=235454\n|Title=The Best of Molly Shannon \n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|3|20}}\n|ShortSummary=The special included material featuring Molly Shannon during her stint on the show. Sketches include \"Mary Katherine Gallagher,\" \"Leg Up,\" \"The Courtney Love Show,\" \"Pretty Living,\" \"Delicious Dish,\" \"Rockettes Auditions,\" \"Monica Lewinsky in Congress,\" \"Fanatic\" (film), \"Blind Date At The Airport,\" \"Veronica and Co.,\" \"Dame Elizabeth Taylor,\" and \"Jeannie Darcy\".\n}}\n\n{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Saturday Night Live (season 26)\n|LineColor=235454\n|Title=Mother's Day Special 2001 \n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|5|13}}\n|ShortSummary=The first SNL Mother's Day special since 1993, the episode featured the cast and their mothers talking about their favorite sketches aired on the show. Sketches included \"Behind the Music: Rock & Roll Heaven\", \"TRL: Gemini's Twin\", \"Mango vs. J.Lo\", \"The Weakest Link\" and more. This special contained a special tribute to singer-songwriter [[Minnie Riperton]], who was the mother of cast member Maya Rudolph.\n}}\n}}\n\n==''The Ladies Man'' film==\n{{main|The Ladies Man (2000 film)}}\nBased on [[Leon Phelps]]' popular sketches, ''[[The Ladies Man (2000 film)|The Ladies Man]]'' film was released on October 13, 2000. The film's star [[Tim Meadows]] left Saturday Night Live at the end of the previous season but returned to promote the film in the first episode of this season. Cast members [[Will Ferrell]] and [[Chris Parnell]] and former [[Saturday Night Live|SNL]] cast member [[Mark McKinney]] co-starred in this film. The movie was panned by critics and flopped at the box office.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[History of Saturday Night Live (2000\u20132005)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Saturday Night Live}}\n\n[[Category:Saturday Night Live seasons|26]]\n[[Category:Saturday Night Live in the 2000s]]\n[[Category:2000 American television seasons]]\n[[Category:2001 American television seasons]]\n[[Category:Television programs directed by Beth McCarthy-Miller]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=December 2008}}\n\n{{Infobox television season\n| season_number = 26\n| bgcolour = #235454\n| image = SNLseason26.jpg\n| image_size = 250\n| image_alt = The title card for the twenty-sixth season of ''Saturday Night Live''.\n| caption =\n| starring =\n| country = United States\n| num_episodes = 20\n| network = [[NBC]]\n| first_aired = {{Start date|2000|10|07}}\n| last_aired = {{End date|2001|05|19}}\n| prev_season = [[Saturday Night Live (season 25)|season 25]]\n| next_season = [[Saturday Night Live (season 27)|season 27]]\n| episode_list = List of Saturday Night Live episodes\n}}\n\nThe '''twenty-sixth season''' of ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', an American [[sketch comedy]] series, originally aired in the United States on [[NBC]] between October 7, 2000, and May 19, 2001.\n\nThis season featured satire of the [[2000 United States presidential election|2000 U.S presidential election]], including the [[Republican Party (United States) presidential primaries, 2000|Republican]] and [[Democratic Party (United States) presidential primaries, 2000|Democratic]] primaries, the campaigns of [[Al Gore presidential campaign, 2000|Vice President Gore]], [[George W. Bush presidential campaign, 2000|Texas Governor George W. Bush]], and [[Ralph Nader presidential campaign, 2000|Ralph Nader]], the [[Florida election recount]], and the [[Bush v. Gore]] case that came before the [[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S. Supreme Court]].\n\n==Cast==\nBefore the start of the season, [[Tim Meadows]], [[Cheri Oteri]] and [[Colin Quinn]] left the show. With the three of them gone, the show added two new cast members. ''SNL'' head writer [[Tina Fey]] and [[The Second City|Second City]] comedian [[Jerry Minor]] joined the cast as featured players at the start of the season. Fey had been a writer on the show since 1997 and began as the show's head writer in 1999. [[Rachel Dratch]] and [[Maya Rudolph]] remained featured players. Minor was let go following this season.\n\nThis would be [[Molly Shannon]]'s final season on the show. Leaving mid-season, She surpassed [[Victoria Jackson]] as the show's longest-serving female cast member ([[Amy Poehler]] would later surpass Shannon's record seven years later).\n\n[[Chris Parnell]] was fired at the end of this season, but then rehired midway through the next season. Executive producer [[Lorne Michaels]] would later admit he made a mistake in firing Parnell from the cast and wanted him back.<ref name=ParnellVulture>{{cite web|last1=Graham|first1=Mark|title=''Archer''\u2019s Chris Parnell Talks Well-Endowed Cartoon Characters, Being Fired From ''SNL'' Twice|url=http://www.vulture.com/2010/01/chris_parnell.html|website=Vulture|accessdate=April 12, 2015|date=January 14, 2010}}</ref>\n\nWith [[Colin Quinn]]'s anchor seat on \"[[Weekend Update]]\" empty, executive producer [[Lorne Michaels]] decided to go back to the format used in the 1970s with two anchors. [[Jimmy Fallon]] and head writer [[Tina Fey]] were picked to anchor the segment together. Because of Fey's head writer status, she would rarely make appearances in segments other than \"Weekend Update\".\n\n===Cast roster===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Repertory players'''\n*'''[[Jimmy Fallon]]'''\n*[[Will Ferrell]]\n*[[Ana Gasteyer]]\n*[[Darrell Hammond]]\n*[[Chris Kattan]]\n*[[Tracy Morgan]]\n*[[Chris Parnell]]\n*[[Horatio Sanz]]\n*[[Molly Shannon]] <small>(final episode: February 17, 2001)</small>\n{{col-2}}\n'''Featured players'''\n*[[Rachel Dratch]]\n*'''[[Tina Fey]]'''\n*[[Jerry Minor]]\n*[[Maya Rudolph]]\n{{col-end}}\n<small>'''bold''' denotes \"[[Weekend Update]]\" anchor</small>\n\n==Writers==\n{{main|List of Saturday Night Live writers#season 26}}\n[[Jim Downey (comedian)|Jim Downey]] rejoins the writing staff this season.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of Saturday Night Live episodes}}\n<onlyinclude>{{#invoke:Episode table|main\n|background=#235454\n|overall= \n|season=\n|aux1=\n|aux1T=Host\n|aux2=33\n|aux2T=Musical guest(s)\n|airdate=\n|episodes=\n\n{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Saturday Night Live (season 26)\n|EpisodeNumber=486\n|EpisodeNumber2=1\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2000|10|7}}\n|RTitle=[[Rob Lowe]]\n|Aux1=[[Eminem]]\n|ShortSummary=\n*Eminem performs \"[[Stan (song)|Stan]]\" (with [[Dido (singer)|Dido]]) and \"[[The Real Slim Shady]]\", and also appeared during Weekend Update.\n*[[Ralph Nader presidential campaign, 2000|2000 Presidential candidate]] [[Ralph Nader]] made a [[cameo appearance]] during the \"Backstage\" sketch.\n*[[Brendan Fraser]] cameos in the \"Personal Profile\" sketch featuring Chris Kattan getting ready for the next sketch like the athletes featured in the Olympic Profiles segment.\n*The [[George W. Bush]]/[[Al Gore]] presidential debate sketch in this episode is credited with coining the word \"[[strategery]]\".\n*[[Tina Fey]] and [[Jerry Minor]]'s first episode as cast members.\n*[[Jimmy Fallon]] and [[Tina Fey]]'s first episode as [[Weekend Update]] co-anchors (the first co-anchors since [[Saturday Night Live (season 3)|season 3]] with [[Dan Aykroyd]] and [[Jane Curtin]]).\n*Former cast member [[Tim Meadows]] appears on ''Weekend Update'' to promote ''[[The Ladies Man (2000 film)|The Ladies Man]]'', a film produced by [[SNL Studios]].\n|LineColor=235454\n}}\n\n{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Saturday Night Live (season 26)\n|EpisodeNumber=487\n|EpisodeNumber2=2\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2000|10|14}}\n|RTitle=[[Kate Hudson]]\n|Aux1=[[Radiohead]]\n|ShortSummary=\n*Radiohead performs \"[[The National Anthem (song)|The National Anthem]]\" and \"[[Idioteque]]\".\n*[[Nomar Garciaparra]] appears as himself during a Sully and Denise sketch.\n|LineColor=235454\n}}\n\n{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Saturday Night Live (season 26)\n|EpisodeNumber=488\n|EpisodeNumber2=3\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2000|10|21}}\n|RTitle=[[Dana Carvey]]\n|Aux1=[[The Wallflowers]]\n|ShortSummary=\n*The Wallflowers performs \"[[(Breach)|Sleepwalker]]\" and \"Hand Me Down\".\n*[[Baha Men]] makes a surprise appearance and performs \"[[Who Let the Dogs Out?]]\".\n*[[Robert De Niro]] appears as himself during Weekend Update to discuss Jimmy Fallon's negative review of ''[[Meet the Parents]]'' from the previous episode.\n|LineColor=235454\n}}\n\n{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Saturday Night Live (season 26)\n|EpisodeNumber=489\n|EpisodeNumber2=4\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2000|11|4}}\n|RTitle=[[Charlize Theron]]\n|Aux1=[[Paul Simon]]\n|ShortSummary=\n*Paul Simon performs \"Hurricane Eye\" and \"Old\".\n*SNL writer and stand up Hugh Fink appears as himself on Weekend Update in a commentary on [[Judaism]] and [[Joe Lieberman]].\n|LineColor=235454\n}}\n\n{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Saturday Night Live (season 26)\n|EpisodeNumber=490\n|EpisodeNumber2=5\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2000|11|11}}\n|RTitle=[[Calista Flockhart]]\n|Aux1=[[Ricky Martin]]\n|ShortSummary=\n*Ricky Martin performs \"[[She Bangs]]\" and \"[[Loaded (Ricky Martin song)|Loaded]]\".\n*Chris Kattan impersonates Ricky Martin right before the real Ricky Martin performs the song \"Loaded\" (from Martin's album ''[[Sound Loaded]]'').\n*[[Giovanni Hidalgo]] performs percussion during Ricky Martin's musical performances. \n|LineColor=235454\n}}\n\n{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Saturday Night Live (season 26)\n|EpisodeNumber=491\n|EpisodeNumber2=6\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2000|11|18}}\n|RTitle=[[Tom Green]]\n|Aux1=[[David Gray (musician)|David Gray]]\n|ShortSummary=\n*David Gray performs \"[[Babylon (David Gray song)|Babylon]]\" and appears in the \"Wedding\" sketch.\n*[[Drew Barrymore]] is in the audience and mentioned in the monologue by Tom Green.\n*[[Gwyneth Paltrow]] appears on Weekend Update.\n*Tom's parents Mary Jane Green and Richard Green appear in the opening monologue and the \"Wedding\" sketch.\n*Shawn Greenson, [[Derek Harvie]], and Glenn Humplik appear in the \"Wedding\" sketch.\n*Tom Green brought in his own writers for this episode, which didn't please the cast.<ref>{{cite book|title=Live From New York, The Uncensored History of Saturday Night Live}}</ref>\n|LineColor=235454\n}}\n\n{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Saturday Night Live (season 26)\n|EpisodeNumber=492\n|EpisodeNumber2=7\n|OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|2000|12|9}}\n|RTitle=[[Val Kilmer]]\n|Aux1=[[U2]]\n|ShortSummary=\n*U2 performs \"[[Beautiful Day]]\" and \"[[Elevation (song)|Elevation]]\".\n*The previous day marked the 20th anniversary of [[Death of John Lennon|John Lennon's assassination]]; [[Bono]] paid tribute to Lennon by singing a verse of \"[[All You Need Is Love]]\" over the end of \"Beautiful Day\".\n*The Director, Associate Directors, and Stage Managers who worked on this episode won a Directors Guild of America Award for Outstanding Directorial Achievement.\n|LineColor=235454\n}}\n\n{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Saturday Night Live (season 26)\n|EpisodeNumber=493\n|EpisodeNumber2=8\n|OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|2000|12|16}}\n|RTitle=[[Lucy Liu]]\n|Aux1=[[Jay-Z]]\n|ShortSummary=\n*Jay-Z performs \"[[I Just Wanna Love U (Give It 2 Me)]]\" and \"Is That Your Chick,\" and cameos in the \"Robert Goulet Rap Album\" sketch.\n*[[Beanie Sigel]] and [[Memphis Bleek]] join Jay-Z for both musical performances and also appear in the \"Robert Goulet Rap Album\" sketch.\n\n|LineColor=235454\n}}\n\n{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Saturday Night Live (season 26)\n|EpisodeNumber=494\n|EpisodeNumber2=9\n|OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|2001|1|13}}\n|RTitle=[[Charlie Sheen]]\n|Aux1=[[Nelly Furtado]]\n|ShortSummary=\n*Nelly Furtado performs \"[[I'm Like a Bird]]\".\n*Charlie Sheen reprises his role as Ricky Vaughn from the ''[[Major League (film)|Major League]]'' films in \"The NFL Pregame\" sketch.\n|LineColor=235454\n}}\n\n{{#invoke:Episode list|sublist|Saturday Night Live (season 26)\n|EpisodeNumber=495\n|EpisodeNumber2=10\n|OriginalAirDate= {{Start date|2001|1|20}}\n|RTitle=[[Mena Suvari]]\n|Aux1=[[Lenny Kravitz]]\n|ShortSummary=\n*Lenny Kravitz performs \"[[Again (Lenny Kravitz song)|Again]]\" and \"[[Mr. Cab Driver]],\" and appears in two live sketches as himself; one as holding auditions for Kyle 